PM1jaQBBZcFiNnMNg9BPiQgGmpl4--HpYpJOOt2VSn2sQVhTvvSZCpJaIM_eaTbwqZdCEaeFY5O=
ciC_zOwMcxgeNuQI56xK8NehTvBmUckk2DVTRXsBke6oscKaotWpyi3ASxkVx8tGZTXUeogUNP5=
CvFIEEvSGe5dV_vfh3m7fx-fARO5vaRbzmlFPGmGK97OnYsc6UMAKv_Iz7S9Bj5V2pS0Fj98Y5S=
NYx4ZKyj2uD980cEG6gGZ_bPmr0eM0QzRLAPZnwaeG2iNcJOsJvCYAI-Xl-gk7jMEghSVNzqfUR=
_4X-AAOVcZY] is built on DeFi rails, but unlike them, you wouldn=E2=80=99t =
know that from looking at their site. DeFi is part of Fairmint=E2=80=99s te=
ch stack, not its main value prop.=C2=A0
Meet Fairmint
Fairmint is like Kickstarter on steroids, mixed with Carta, embedded right =
in the products we use and love. They=E2=80=99re building the picks and sho=
vels for founders to turn their equity into the most powerful tool to engag=
e with their contributors.=C2=A0
Equity powers the entire stack of entrepreneurship and is the most powerful=
 tool to align financial interests. It has a simple value prop: help make t=
his company more valuable, and you will be rewarded. Equity is the reason s=
tartups can write that bullet that goes something like...
Be a team player. Be willing to get your hands dirty, go above and beyond t=
he responsibilities of your role, and do whatever it takes to help this com=
pany reach its full potential!=C2=A0
=2E..on every job description, with a straight face.=C2=A0
It is also the greatest wealth-building financial instrument. Until now, th=
e absence of a single, global, open, and interoperable system of record for=
 equity has hampered innovation and the democratization of equity ownership=
=2E=C2=A0
Luckily, global, open, and interoperable systems of record are what crypto =
does best, and Fairmint is using it to build =E2=80=9Csoftware-powered fina=
ncing services to raise capital continuously from anyone who supports their=
 product and mission.=E2=80=9D
Fairmint created the Continuous Agreement for Future Equity [https://email.=
mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUM2O8yAMfJpyS8RvSw8c9vK9RgTESVETkw_MrvL2S9vDSpYse-wZ=
e6InWHM53ZErsVahTGl24iqtMvrOZqdnYY1lqU5LAdh92hyVBuxoYUvRU8r43uBcGvZw3HvNZdB=
2iepuuNYCgrKdT0UbrNXspTP5NifACA6-oZwZgW3uQXTUi_q6yH89Fp_KnpDGmHsV_QJDzEgJW2=
518OvrFkAallyGpVErMMD_lujs0yw5ySUXQtyFMorfRjH6ut1ANnng86L5vsqxtlDJx2dX2Flxm=
CnkknDt8PPhd9jeQH9z6nlv2LknQB82mD8O0Mez90N0HuAQfuoGRFA-zZct9na9Gm1YV5tzdw__=
hH4BW2aClQ] (CAFE), an updated version of Y Combinator=E2=80=99s SAFE [http=
s://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMuOwyAM_JpyjHgm6YHDXvobEQ-3RSUQgdkof78kPa=
xkydaM7PGMMwivXA695YqkVShL8JqNfBZK3onX0rNZzSTU5VkAVhOixtKAbM3G4AyGnK4NSrkib=
83FcwQprFNsEnzmILmV9g6KUsqksuTUWUzzAZIDDb9QjpyARP1G3OpN_Nz4o9e-78Ph8mpDMpjL=
0MeO-uzaCglrn0nQnHLKGLszoQSdBjaYGifgjW_pc5N0ffGhNlvRuM95gBSdMtpcQnp1-vM2K8S=
L6GaW3teWAh4LJGMj-K9P_CZzvY3HBjrBXiMgQvmCp_l5GkclFelqPveM0r_QHxIQeKo], whic=
h lets a company=E2=80=99s stakeholders buy or earn equity in the company, =
at any time, directly from their website. It=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cprogrammabl=
e equity.=E2=80=9D Companies will be able to add an =E2=80=9CInvest=E2=80=
=9D button right to their site as easily as they add a =E2=80=9CBuy with Ap=
ple Pay=E2=80=9D button today.=C2=A0
Importantly, users and investors don=E2=80=99t need to know or care that th=
ey=E2=80=99re dealing with a DeFi product. They only need to think about ho=
w the product benefits them:
Founders benefit because fundraising is no longer a full-time job. On Fairm=
int, founders raise funds on a rolling basis in a =E2=80=9Cset it and forge=
t it=E2=80=9D fashion. They can set up automated incentivization plans and =
align their stakeholders with their success. And it gives them flexibility =
-=C2=A0 if they don=E2=80=99t want to sell and if an IPO is not in the card=
s, their investors can still get liquidity.=C2=A0
Investors benefit because they get a clearer path to liquidity and can inve=
st in the companies they love and trust at stages usually reserved for insi=
ders and VCs.=C2=A0
Users benefit because they can participate in the financial upside, either =
by purchasing shares or earning shares for supporting the company.
Shares sold via Fairmint are dollar-denominated and look like any other inv=
estment you might own.=C2=A0
Fairmint abstracts away a ton of complexity, so users can focus on how they=
 might use Fairmint to grow their business. Our heads are swimming with pos=
sibilities:=C2=A0
What if Wikipedia was owned by the editors?=C2=A0
Could the small businesses that list on Yelp, or the contributors who power=
 its ratings, own shares in the company?=C2=A0
Could Reddit reward its moderators with ownership?=C2=A0
Why couldn=E2=80=99t Airbnb give Hosts equity when they become SuperHosts?=
=C2=A0
Shouldn=E2=80=99t Uber=E2=80=99s drivers own a piece of the business if the=
y maintain a high enough rating over enough rides?=C2=A0
Would writers be less likely to leave Substack if they owned a piece of the=
 company?
What if early users of SaaS products could invest in the company itself? My=
 mom has been singing Zoom=E2=80=99s praises since 2014. She=E2=80=99d be r=
etired if they worked with Fairmint.
What if Taylor Swift=E2=80=99s fans could replace Scooter Braun [https://em=
ail.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2uhCAMhZ9m2Gn4EcUFi7u5r2EQO0oGwUCZiW9_0VncpMmX=
ttDTHmsQ1phOfcSMpGRIk1s067kSshvJoruFKamIy9MzAezGeY2pADnK7J016GK4f1DKJdm0HPq=
OjyPwngEf-ahE94RejEouig7Qk0tnMmVxECxoeEM6YwDi9YZ45If4efDfGm-THODZ2rjXjFNOK_=
aSna0M8MkV2caIkJo5mRKaDN7nBs3pY2ryxz2xmd3a7MZuLkBlrm9zw7jolOBUXQOJ09doxtjIh=
BR0aFlrsh-AF36E16Oj-8rbXOaMxr6uZUjSIeIckwtrbb82s4O_G9WQqXIvweE5QTCzh-XrFX7d=
vU_H8wB9HeAB60Lf4mWgGvpedpJUtSVWn8O_0B81T440]?=C2=A0
And these are just the businesses that have been able to thrive with existi=
ng financial infrastructure. What kinds of businesses could work with Fairm=
int that couldn=E2=80=99t have before?=C2=A0
One area that seems ripe for this model are marketplaces with particularly =
challenging cold-start problems. A marketplace cannot acquire demand if the=
re is no supply, and=C2=A0 the supply side has no incentive to join if the =
demand isn't there. This makes marketplaces extremely difficult and expensi=
ve to build. Many marketplace companies either fail or are forced to raise =
a lot of venture money so they can try to spend their way to liquidity. Wha=
t if, instead, they incentivized early participants with ownership in the c=
ompany? Instead of just =E2=80=9Csupply,=E2=80=9D marketplace participants =
become loyal builders and evangelists.=C2=A0
If companies can provide incentives for early adopters to participate befor=
e critical mass is achieved, they=E2=80=99re more likely to pose a credible=
 threat to incumbents. As Charlie Munger said, =E2=80=9CShow me the incenti=
ves and I=E2=80=99ll show you the outcomes.=E2=80=9D A lot of business mode=
ls that failed in Web 2.0 will become viable in Web3. The next generation o=
f platforms like Homejoy and TaskRabbit, which solved the marketplace liqui=
dity problem only to suffer from =E2=80=9Cplatform leakage=E2=80=9D as cust=
omers and providers took their relationship offline after the first transac=
tion, could stand to benefit from aligning their incentives with the people=
 who do the work.
Coming full-circle, could CAFEs replace the traditional ESOP that has fuele=
d Silicon Valley=E2=80=99s growth, facilitating more liquid employment whil=
e retaining the benefits of equity ownership? The current model -- negotiat=
e an options grant before you=E2=80=99ve started working and slowly earn th=
ose options as you spend more time at the company -- is a clunky solution t=
hat optimizes for lower administrative burden and keeping employees at the =
company. Worse, employees who leave before an exit often can=E2=80=99t affo=
rd to buy shares today and hope for an outcome later, and give up the right=
 to buy their shares, missing out on the upside.=C2=A0
But what if companies could give employees equity on an ongoing basis based=
 on their contributions? There are countless examples of more junior employ=
ees making a bigger impact in two productive years at a company than some e=
xecs make over four years, but the current structure isn=E2=80=99t set up t=
o handle those cases. And ongoing liquidity would be hugely valuable in ens=
uring that all employees are able to make money from the shares they=E2=80=
=99ve earned.=C2=A0
When stakeholders -- partners, investors, creators, evangelists, and employ=
ees -- are properly incentivized, the possibilities dwarf the imagination.=
=C2=A0
Idealism aside, though, Fairmint will face a few key challenges in making t=
hat future a reality.=C2=A0
Ownership Distribution. Nailing an effective ownership distribution that in=
centivizes the right behaviors is VERY hard. Fairmint will need to give com=
panies templates and best practices to help them get started. There will in=
evitably be a period of trial and error here.=C2=A0
Product Marketing. Explaining what Fairmint does is a challenge. They=E2=80=
=99re currently explaining it simply as =E2=80=9Cthe ESOP for customers,=E2=
=80=9D and it seems to be working.=C2=A0
Double-Edged Switching Costs. There=E2=80=99s no such thing as a =E2=80=9Cf=
ree trial=E2=80=9D with Fairmint. Once you decide to use Fairmint and sell =
shares via a CAFE, switching to another model is a huge pain. That creates =
high switching costs, but also barriers to adoption.=C2=A0
Fairmint has its work cut out for it, but we=E2=80=99re rooting for it to s=
ucceed. A world in which Fairmint is successful is the kind of world we wan=
t to live in.=C2=A0
Vision
There=E2=80=99s this recurring theme on the internet (and with people more =
broadly): When something is easy, people will do more of it.=C2=A0
Creating content was the first thing that became easy on the internet, and =
more people began to create content. WordPress turned people into bloggers.=
 YouTube turned them into videographers. Substack is turning us all into ne=
wsletter writers.=C2=A0
Likewise, if creating and sharing value becomes easy, more people will do i=
t.
In the same way the internet was a democratizing force that gave everyone i=
n the world the ability to easily create and share information, the next st=
ep is to give everyone in the world the ability to easily create and share =
value.
Better economic alignment between platforms and participants is coming, and=
 will enable the advent of true stakeholder capitalism to give billions of =
people the opportunity to build wealth alongside the products and services =
they love and use.=C2=A0
New technology is powerful not because of what it can do, but because of wh=
at people can do for other people with it. Crypto can create new financial =
models, and those new financial models can in turn unleash a monsoon of cre=
ativity and new business models. Fairchild Semiconductor=E2=80=99s investor=
s couldn=E2=80=99t have envisioned Fairmint when they decided to incentiviz=
e the Traitorous Eight with upside in the business. But with hindsight, we =
can draw a wavy line from one to the other.=C2=A0
Driven by network effects, technology has radically changed the pace of wea=
lth accumulation. It took Hyatt 63 years to be worth $7 billion. It only to=
ok Airbnb 12 years to be worth $18 billion.=C2=A0
Crypto=E2=80=99s true promise is the ability to usher in a new economic ope=
rating system where distributing that value is as easy as paying payroll. O=
ne that can close the wealth gap by pulling wage earners out of the debt st=
ack and into the equity stack. One that allows people to share in the upsid=
e and ultimately shift the paradigm of ownership to the individuals and com=
munities responsible for creating value. Viewed through that lens, Fairmint=
 is more than a product; it=E2=80=99s a movement.
Trying to write thousands of words every week with a new baby is exhausting=
=2E So since the Zest Tea team sent me s=
ome of their high caffeine teas a cou=
ple of weeks ago, I=E2=80=99ve had one every day. My favorite is the Spiced=
 Chai Infusion Sparkling Tea (please send more, Cou!).=C2=A0
They have more caffeine than coffee, without the jitters or crash, and they=
=E2=80=99ve helped me maintain prolonged focus despite my suboptimal sleep =
schedule. If you=E2=80=99re looking for clarity in the chaos, get yourself =
some Zest, and use code =E2=80=9Cnotboring=E2=80=9D for free US shipping.
Thanks for reading, and see you on Monday,
Packy

